<exercisegroup>
<title>Interpreting matrix equality as a system of equations</title>

<introduction><p>
	In each case,
	determining the variable values that make the matrix equality true.
	In any equality where <m>\zerovec</m> appears,
	assume it represents a zero matrix of appropriate dimensions.
</p></introduction>

<exercise>

	<statement><p><m>\displaystyle
		\begin{bmatrix}
			b + 3 c \amp c + 3 b - 2 a \\
			a + 4 c \amp a - 4 b - 3 c
		\end{bmatrix}
		=
		\begin{amatrix}{rr}
			-5 \amp 3 \\
			-9 \amp 0
		\end{amatrix}
	</m></p></statement>

	<solution><p>
		Comparing corresponding entries on each side of the matrix equality leads to system of equations
		<me>
			\begin{sysofeqns}{rcrcrcr}
				     \amp   \amp   b \amp + \amp 3 c \amp = \amp -5 \\
				-2 a \amp + \amp 3 b \amp + \amp   c \amp = \amp  3 \\
				   a \amp   \amp     \amp + \amp 4 c \amp = \amp -9 \\
				   a \amp - \amp 4 b \amp - \amp 3 c \amp = \amp  0
			\end{sysofeqns}
		</me>.
		Turn this system into an augmented matrix and reduce:
		<me>
			\begin{amatrix}{rrr|r}
				 0 \amp  1 \amp  3 \amp -5 \\
				-2 \amp  3 \amp  1 \amp  3 \\
				 1 \amp  0 \amp  4 \amp -9 \\
				 2 \amp -4 \amp -3 \amp  0
			\end{amatrix}
			\longrightarrow
			\left(\begin{array}{rrr|r}
				1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
				0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp  1 \\
				0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\
				0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp  0
			\end{array}\right)
		</me>.
		This system is consistent with one unique solution <m>a = -1</m>, <m>b = 1</m>, <m>c = -2</m>.
	</p></solution>

</exercise>

<exercise>

	<statement><p><m>\displaystyle
		  k_1 \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
		+ k_2 \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
		= \begin{amatrix}{r} -3 \\ -7 \\ -5 \end{amatrix}
	</m></p></statement>

	<solution>

		<p>
		First compute the left-hand side to a single column matrix:
		<md>

			<mrow>
				  k_1 \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
				+ k_2 \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
				\amp
				= \begin{amatrix}{r} 3 k_1 \\ 2 k_1 \\ k_1 \end{amatrix}
				+ \begin{amatrix}{r} 7 k_2 \\ 3 k_2 \\ k_2 \end{amatrix}
			</mrow>

			<mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 3 k_1 + 7 k_2 \\ 2 k_1 + 3 k_2 \\ k_1 + k_2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>

		</md>.
		Our simplified matrix equality is now
		<me>
			\begin{bmatrix} 3 k_1 + 7 k_2 \\ 2 k_1 + 3 k_2 \\ k_1 + k_2 \end{bmatrix}
			= \begin{amatrix}{r} -3 \\ -7 \\ -5 \end{amatrix}
		</me>.
		Comparing corresponding entries on each side of the matrix equality leads to system of equations
		<me>
			\begin{sysofeqns}{rcrcr}
				3 k_1 \amp + \amp 7 k_2 \amp = \amp -3 \\
				2 k_1 \amp + \amp 3 k_2 \amp = \amp -7 \\
				  k_1 \amp + \amp   k_2 \amp = \amp -5
			\end{sysofeqns}
		</me>.
		Turn this system into an augmented matrix and reduce:
		<me>
			\begin{amatrix}{rr|r}
				3 \amp 7 \amp -3 \\
				2 \amp 3 \amp -7 \\
				1 \amp 1 \amp -5
			\end{amatrix}
			\longrightarrow
			\begin{amatrix}{rrr}
				1 \amp 0 \amp -8 \\
				0 \amp 1 \amp  3 \\
				0 \amp 0 \amp  0
			\end{amatrix}
		</me>.
		This system is consistent with one unique solution <m>k_1 = -8</m>, <m>b = 3</m>.
		You may test that this is the correct solution by recomputing the matrix algebra on the left-hand side of the original matrix equality with those values in place of <m>k_1</m> and <m>k_2</m>.
		</p>

		<aside><title>Identify the pattern</title><p>
			Compare the augmented system matrix we produced with three column matrices in the original matrix equality <mdash />
			what do you notice?
		</p></aside>

	</solution>

</exercise>

<exercise>

	<statement><p><m>\displaystyle
		  c_1 \begin{amatrix}{r}  0 \\ -1 \\  1 \end{amatrix}
		+ c_2 \begin{amatrix}{r}  1 \\ -2 \\ -1 \end{amatrix}
		=     \begin{amatrix}{r} -5 \\ 11 \\  5 \end{amatrix}
	</m></p></statement>

	<solution>

		<p>
		First compute the left-hand side to a single column matrix:
		<md>

			<mrow>
				  c_1 \begin{amatrix}{r} 0 \\ -1 \\  1 \end{amatrix}
				+ c_2 \begin{amatrix}{r} 1 \\ -2 \\ -1 \end{amatrix}
				\amp
				= \begin{amatrix}{r}  0  \\ -  c_1 \\  c_1 \end{amatrix}
				+ \begin{amatrix}{r} c_2 \\ -2 c_2 \\ -c_2 \end{amatrix}
			</mrow>

			<mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} c_1 \\ 2 k_1 + 3 k_2 \\ k_1 + k_2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>

		</md>.
		Our simplified matrix equality is now
		<me>
			\begin{bmatrix} c_2 \\ -c_1 - 2 c_2 \\ c_1 - c_2 \end{bmatrix}
			= \begin{amatrix}{r} -5 \\ 11 \\ 5 \end{amatrix}
		</me>.
		Comparing corresponding entries on each side of the matrix equality leads to system of equations
		<me>
			\begin{sysofeqns}{rcrcr}
				     \amp   \amp   c_2 \amp = \amp -5 \\
				-c_1 \amp - \amp 2 c_2 \amp = \amp 11 \\
				 c_1 \amp - \amp   c_2 \amp = \amp  5
			\end{sysofeqns}
		</me>.
		Turn this system into an augmented matrix and reduce:
		<me>
			\begin{amatrix}{rr|r}
				 0 \amp  1 \amp -5 \\
				-1 \amp -2 \amp 11 \\
				 1 \amp -1 \amp  5
			\end{amatrix}
			\longrightarrow
			\begin{amatrix}{rrr}
				1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
				0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
				0 \amp 0 \amp 1
			\end{amatrix}
		</me>.
		This system is inconsistent,
		so there is no combination of values for <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m> that make the original matrix equality true.
		</p>

		<p>
		<alert>Careful:</alert>
		It is tempting to attempt to solve the system of equations directly,
		without using an augmented matrix,
		as we clearly have <m>c_2 = -5</m> from the first equation,
		and then we can use the third equation to solve <m>c_1 = 0</m>.
		But if you substitute those two values into the left-hand side of the original matrix equality and recompute the matrix algebra,
		you will find that the matrix equality is not true for these values.
		The reason for this is that the original matrix equality leads to a system of <em>three</em> equations,
		and we cannot ignore any one equation in that system.
		</p>

	</solution>

</exercise>

<exercise>

	<statement><p><m>\displaystyle
		  k_1 \begin{amatrix}{rr} 0 \amp  2 \\ -2 \amp 1 \end{amatrix}
		+ k_2 \begin{amatrix}{rr} 1 \amp -2 \\  3 \amp 2 \end{amatrix}
		+ k_3 \begin{amatrix}{rr} 2 \amp -2 \\  3 \amp 5 \end{amatrix}
		+ k_4 \begin{amatrix}{rr} 1 \amp  0 \\  4 \amp 3 \end{amatrix}
		=
		\zerovec
	</m></p></statement>

	<solution>

		<p>
		First compute the left-hand side to a single matrix:
		<md>

			<mrow>
				\amp
				  k_1 \begin{amatrix}{rr} 0 \amp  2 \\ -2 \amp 1 \end{amatrix}
				+ k_2 \begin{amatrix}{rr} 1 \amp -2 \\  3 \amp 2 \end{amatrix}
				+ k_3 \begin{amatrix}{rr} 2 \amp -2 \\  3 \amp 5 \end{amatrix}
				+ k_4 \begin{amatrix}{rr} 1 \amp  0 \\  4 \amp 3 \end{amatrix}
			</mrow>

			<mrow>
				\amp
				= \begin{bmatrix}   0   \amp  2 k_1 \\ -2 k_1 \amp   k_1 \end{bmatrix}
				+ \begin{bmatrix}  k_2  \amp -2 k_2 \\  3 k_2 \amp 2 k_2 \end{bmatrix}
				+ \begin{bmatrix} 2 k_3 \amp -2 k_3 \\  3 k_3 \amp 5 k_3 \end{bmatrix}
				+ \begin{bmatrix}  k_4  \amp    0   \\  4 k_4 \amp 3 k_4 \end{bmatrix}
			</mrow>

			<mrow>
				\amp =
				\begin{bmatrix}
					           k_2 + 2 k_3 +   k_4 \amp 2 k_1 - 2 k_2 - 2 k_3         \\
					-2 k_1 + 3 k_2 + 3 k_3 + 4 k_4 \amp   k_1 + 2 k_2 + 5 k_3 + 3 k_4
				\end{bmatrix}
			</mrow>

		</md>.
		In the context of the original matrix equality,
		the <m>\zerovec</m> symbol on the right-hand side should represent the <m>2 \times 2</m> zero matrix,
		and so our simplified matrix equality is now
		<me>
			\begin{bmatrix}
				           k_2 + 2 k_3 +   k_4 \amp 2 k_1 - 2 k_2 - 2 k_3         \\
				-2 k_1 + 3 k_2 + 3 k_3 + 4 k_4 \amp   k_1 + 2 k_2 + 5 k_3 + 3 k_4
			\end{bmatrix}
			=
			\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
		</me>.
		Comparing corresponding entries on each side of the matrix equality leads to homogeneous system of equations
		<me>
			\begin{sysofeqns}{rcrcrcrcr}
				       \amp   \amp   k_2 \amp + \amp 2 k_3 \amp + \amp   k_4 \amp = \amp 0 \\
				 2 k_1 \amp - \amp 2 k_2 \amp - \amp 2 k_3 \amp   \amp       \amp = \amp 0 \\
				-2 k_1 \amp + \amp 3 k_2 \amp + \amp 3 k_3 \amp + \amp 4 k_4 \amp = \amp 0 \\
				   k_1 \amp + \amp 2 k_2 \amp + \amp 5 k_3 \amp + \amp 3 k_4 \amp = \amp 0
			\end{sysofeqns}
		</me>.
		Since the system is homogeneous,
		we reduce only with the coefficient matrix:
		<me>
			\begin{amatrix}{rrrr}
				 0 \amp  1 \amp  2 \amp 1 \\
				 2 \amp -2 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\
				-2 \amp  3 \amp  3 \amp 4 \\
				 1 \amp  2 \amp  5 \amp 3
			\end{amatrix}
			\longrightarrow
			\begin{amatrix}{rrrr}
				1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp  4 \\
				0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp  7 \\
				0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -3 \\
				0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp  0
			\end{amatrix}
		</me>.
		This system is consistent
		(as all homogeneous systems are)
		but the solution requires a parameter,
		so in fact there are an <em>infinite</em> number of combinations of scalar values for <m>k_1,k_2,k_3,k_4</m> that make the original matrix equality true.
		In particular,
		if we assign parameter <m>k_4 = t</m>,
		the general solution is
		<md><mrow>
			k_1 \amp = -4 t \text{,} \amp
			k_2 \amp = -7 t \text{,} \amp
			k_3 \amp =  3 t \text{,} \amp
			k_4 \amp =    t \text{.}
		</mrow></md>
		</p>

		<aside><title>Identify the pattern</title><p>
			Compare the coefficient matrix we produced with the four <m>2 \times 2</m> matrices in the original matrix equality <mdash />
			what do you notice?
		</p></aside>

		<p>
		<alert>Careful:</alert>
		We may have been misled by the zero matrix on the right-hand side of the original matrix equality,
		and decided that <em>the</em> solution must be to set each of <m>k_1,k_2,k_3,k_4</m> to <m>0</m>.
		While that is <em>one possible</em> solution to the matrix equation
		(which we would call the <term><xref ref="definition-row-red-trivial-sol" text="title" /></term>),
		by re-interpreting the matrix equation as a <em>system of (ordinary) equations</em>,
		we were able to arrive at the <em>complete</em> collection of <em>all possible</em> solutions to the matrix equation.
		So while it is <em>possible</em> to make the matrix equality true by setting each of <m>k_1,k_2,k_3,k_4</m> to <m>0</m>,
		it is also possible, for example, by setting
		<md><mrow>
			k_1 \amp = -4 \text{,} \amp
			k_2 \amp = -7 \text{,} \amp
			k_3 \amp =  3 \text{,} \amp
			k_4 \amp =  1 \text{.}
		</mrow></md>
		</p>

	</solution>

</exercise>

<exercise>

	<statement><p><m>\displaystyle
		  c_1 \begin{amatrix}{rr} 1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 3 \\ -2 \amp 0 \end{amatrix}
		+ c_2 \begin{amatrix}{rr} 1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 3 \\  1 \amp 1 \end{amatrix}
		+ c_3 \begin{amatrix}{rr} 1 \amp 3 \\ 1 \amp 3 \\  3 \amp 1 \end{amatrix}
		= \zerovec
	</m></p></statement>

	<solution>

		<p>
		First compute the left-hand side to a single matrix:
		<md>

			<mrow>
				\amp
				  c_1 \begin{amatrix}{rr} 1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp 3 \\ -2 \amp 0 \end{amatrix}
				+ c_2 \begin{amatrix}{rr} 1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 3 \\  1 \amp 1 \end{amatrix}
				+ c_3 \begin{amatrix}{rr} 1 \amp 3 \\ 1 \amp 3 \\  3 \amp 1 \end{amatrix}
			</mrow>

			<mrow>
				\amp
				= \begin{bmatrix} c_1 \amp  c_1  \\ 2 c_1 \amp 3 c_1 \\ -2 c_1 \amp  0  \end{bmatrix}
				+ \begin{bmatrix} c_2 \amp 2 c_2 \\  c_2  \amp 3 c_2 \\   c_2  \amp c_2 \end{bmatrix}
				+ \begin{bmatrix} c_3 \amp 3 c_3 \\  c_3  \amp 3 c_3 \\  3 c_3 \amp c_3 \end{bmatrix}
			</mrow>

			<mrow>
				\amp =
				\begin{bmatrix}
					   c_1 +   c_2 +   c_3 \amp
					   c_1 + 2 c_2 + 3 c_3 \\
					 2 c_1 +   c_2 +   c_3 \amp
					 3 c_1 + 3 c_2 + 3 c_3 \\
					-2 c_1 +   c_2 + 3 c_3 \amp
					           c_2 +   c_3
				\end{bmatrix}
			</mrow>

		</md>.
		In the context of the original matrix equality,
		the <m>\zerovec</m> symbol on the right-hand side should represent the <m>3 \times 2</m> zero matrix,
		and so our simplified matrix equality is now
		<me>
			\begin{bmatrix}
				   c_1 +   c_2 +   c_3 \amp
				   c_1 + 2 c_2 + 3 c_3 \\
				 2 c_1 +   c_2 +   c_3 \amp
				 3 c_1 + 3 c_2 + 3 c_3 \\
				-2 c_1 +   c_2 + 3 c_3 \amp
				           c_2 +   c_3
			\end{bmatrix}
			=
			\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
		</me>.
		Comparing corresponding entries on each side of the matrix equality leads to homogeneous system of equations
		<me>
			\begin{sysofeqns}{rcrcrcr}
				   c_1 \amp + \amp   c_2 \amp + \amp   c_3 \amp = \amp 0 \\
				   c_1 \amp + \amp 2 c_2 \amp + \amp 3 c_3 \amp = \amp 0 \\
				 2 c_1 \amp + \amp   c_2 \amp + \amp   c_3 \amp = \amp 0 \\
				 3 c_1 \amp + \amp 3 c_2 \amp + \amp 3 c_3 \amp = \amp 0 \\
				-2 c_1 \amp + \amp   c_2 \amp + \amp 3 c_3 \amp = \amp 0 \\
				       \amp   \amp   c_2 \amp + \amp   c_3 \amp = \amp 0
			\end{sysofeqns}
		</me>.
		Since the system is homogeneous,
		we reduce only with the coefficient matrix:
		<me>
			\begin{amatrix}{rrr}
				 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
				 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
				 2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\
				 3 \amp 3 \amp 3 \\
				-2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\
				 0 \amp 1 \amp 1
			\end{amatrix}
			\longrightarrow
			\begin{amatrix}{rrr}
				1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
				0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
				0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
				0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
				0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
				0 \amp 0 \amp 0
			\end{amatrix}
		</me>.
		This system is consistent
		(as all homogeneous systems are)
		with one unique solution,
		the trivial one:
		<m>c_1 = 0</m>, <m>c_2 = 0</m>, and <m>c_3 = 0</m>.
		</p>

		<aside><title>Identify the pattern</title><p>
			Compare the coefficient matrix we produced with the three <m>3 \times 2</m> matrices in the original matrix equality <mdash />
			what do you notice?
		</p></aside>

		<p>
		<alert>Careful:</alert>
		We may have been misled by the zero matrix on the right-hand side of the original matrix equality,
		and prematurely jumped to the conclusion that the <em>only</em> solution must be to set each of <m>c_1,c_2,c_3</m> to <m>0</m>
		(the <term><xref ref="definition-row-red-trivial-sol" text="title" /></term>).
		While that turned out to be the case this time,
		it is important that we went through the full process of re-interpreting the matrix equation as a <em>system of (ordinary) equations</em> so that we could confirm that the trivial solution was indeed the <em>only</em> solution.
		</p>

	</solution>

</exercise>

</exercisegroup>
